{"key":"post-14630514","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>14630514</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;bbox244 said:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Also, another way to calibrate your hygrometer is to use the salt water method, I just posted about this a couple days ago, but basically, salt and water has a critical evaporation potential of 75%, so take a ziplock with a bowl of salt water in it, and put in your hygrometer, after an hour, tune it to 75 and your done.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;That method is not appropriate for mushroom growing.&amp;nbsp; Hygrometers are only accurate over a tiny portion of the scale.&amp;nbsp; Always calibrate at the level you'll be operating at.&amp;nbsp; That means use a damp towel and adjust for 99%.&amp;nbsp; The salt method is accurate for humidors, which run at 70% to 75%.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>14630861</next>\n<prev>14630245</prev>\n<first>14623042</first>\n<last>14649647</last>\n<when>1308366648</when>\n<utime>06/18/11 06:10 AM</utime>\n</post>"}